{
  "answer": "**In Manusmṛti 6.41–6.42, the conduct prescribed for the wandering ascetic (parivrajaka, here termed a sage or ascetic who \"should wander\") is as follows:**\n\n> Having gone forth from his house, furnished with the means of purification, a sage should wander as an ascetic, indifferent to those desires that have been gratified.[^1]  \n> He should always wander alone, without a companion, for the sake of perfection; seeing the perfection of one who is alone, he neither abandons nor is abandoned.[^2]\n\nThese verses occur in the section outlining the duties of the *samnyāsin* (renouncer) in the fourth *āśrama*, after the forest-dweller stage. The broader context (e.g., Mn_6.33–6.43) elaborates further on the ascetic's lifestyle: without fire or home, resorting to villages only for alms, with mind fixed in contemplation.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 6*, [verse 41](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/06/translation/#p-unknown41).  \n[^2]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 6*, [verse 42](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/06/translation/#p-unknown42).  \n[^3]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 6*, [/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/06/translation/](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/06/translation/).",
